#: src/distribution.md:1
msgid "Distribution"
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:3
msgid "Source Distribution"
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:5
msgid ""
"Maturin supports building through `pyproject.toml`. To use it, create a "
"`pyproject.toml` next to your `Cargo.toml` with the following content:"
msgstr ""
"maturin 支援透過 `pyproject.toml` 進行建置。若要使用此功能，請在 `Cargo."
"toml` 旁建立一個內容如下的 `pyproject.toml`："

#: src/distribution.md:7
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"[build-system]\n"
"requires = [\"maturin>=0.14,<0.15\"]\n"
"build-backend = \"maturin\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:13
msgid ""
"If a `pyproject.toml` with a `[build-system]` entry is present, maturin can "
"build a source distribution of your package when `--sdist` is specified. The "
"source distribution will contain the same files as `cargo package`. To only "
"build a source distribution, use the `maturin sdist` command."
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:16
msgid ""
"You can then e.g. install your package with `pip install .`. With `pip "
"install . -v` you can see the output of cargo and maturin."
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:18
msgid ""
"You can use the options `compatibility`, `skip-auditwheel`, `bindings`, "
"`strip` and common Cargo build options such as `features` under `[tool."
"maturin]` the same way you would when running maturin directly. The "
"`bindings` key is required for cffi and bin projects as those can't be "
"automatically detected. Currently, all builds are in release mode (see [this "
"thread](https://discuss.python.org/t/pep-517-debug-vs-release-builds/1924) "
"for details)."
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:21
msgid ""
"For a non-manylinux build with cffi bindings you could use the following:"
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:23
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"[build-system]\n"
"requires = [\"maturin>=0.14,<0.15\"]\n"
"build-backend = \"maturin\"\n"
"\n"
"[tool.maturin]\n"
"bindings = \"cffi\"\n"
"compatibility = \"linux\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:33
msgid ""
"`manylinux` option is also accepted as an alias of `compatibility` for "
"backward compatibility with old version of maturin."
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:35
msgid ""
"To include arbitrary files in the sdist for use during compilation specify "
"`include` as an array of `path` globs with `format` set to `sdist`:"
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:37
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"[tool.maturin]\n"
"include = [{ path = \"path/**/*\", format = \"sdist\" }]\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:42
msgid "Build Wheels"
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:44
msgid ""
"For portability reasons, native python modules on linux must only "
"dynamically link a set of very few libraries which are installed basically "
"everywhere, hence the name manylinux. The pypa offers special docker images "
"and a tool called [auditwheel](https://github.com/pypa/auditwheel/) to "
"ensure compliance with the [manylinux rules](https://peps.python.org/"
"pep-0599/#the-manylinux2014-policy)). If you want to publish widely usable "
"wheels for linux pypi, **you need to use a manylinux docker image** or "
"[build with zig](#use-zig)."
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:48
msgid ""
"The Rust compiler since version 1.64 [requires at least glibc 2.17](https://"
"blog.rust-lang.org/2022/08/01/Increasing-glibc-kernel-requirements.html), so "
"you need to use at least manylinux2014. For publishing, we recommend "
"enforcing the same manylinux version as the image with the manylinux flag, e."
"g. use `--manylinux 2014` if you are building in `quay.io/pypa/"
"manylinux2014_x86_64`. The [PyO3/maturin-action](https://github.com/PyO3/"
"maturin-action) github action already takes care of this if you set e.g. "
"`manylinux: 2014`."
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:52
msgid ""
"maturin contains a reimplementation of auditwheel automatically checks the "
"generated library and gives the wheel the proper platform tag."
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:54
msgid "If your system's glibc is too new, it will assign the `linux` tag."
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:55
msgid ""
"If you link other shared libraries, maturin will try to bundle them within "
"the wheel, note that this requires [patchelf](https://github.com/NixOS/"
"patchelf), it can be installed along with maturin from PyPI: `pip install "
"maturin[patchelf]`."
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:58
msgid ""
"You can also manually disable those checks and directly use native linux "
"target with `--manylinux off`."
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:60
msgid ""
"For full manylinux compliance you need to compile in a CentOS docker "
"container. The [pyo3/maturin](https://ghcr.io/pyo3/maturin) image is based "
"on the manylinux2010 image, and passes arguments to the `maturin` binary. "
"You can use it like this:"
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:67
msgid ""
"Note that this image is very basic and only contains python, maturin and "
"stable Rust. If you need additional tools, you can run commands inside the "
"manylinux container. See [konstin/complex-manylinux-maturin-docker](https://"
"github.com/konstin/complex-manylinux-maturin-docker) for a small educational "
"example or [nanoporetech/fast-ctc-decode](https://github.com/nanoporetech/"
"fast-ctc-decode/blob/b226ea0f2b2f4f474eff47349703d57d2ea4801b/.github/"
"workflows/publish.yml) for a real world setup."
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:72
msgid ""
"```\n"
"Usage: maturin build [OPTIONS] [ARGS]...\n"
"\n"
"Arguments:\n"
"  [ARGS]...\n"
"          Rustc flags\n"
"\n"
"Options:\n"
"  -r, --release\n"
"          Build artifacts in release mode, with optimizations\n"
"\n"
"      --strip\n"
"          Strip the library for minimum file size\n"
"\n"
"      --sdist\n"
"          Build a source distribution\n"
"\n"
"      --compatibility [<compatibility>...]\n"
"          Control the platform tag on linux.\n"
"\n"
"          Options are `manylinux` tags (for example `manylinux2014`/"
"`manylinux_2_24`) or `musllinux`\n"
"          tags (for example `musllinux_1_2`) and `linux` for the native "
"linux tag.\n"
"\n"
"          Note that `manylinux1` and `manylinux2010` is unsupported by the "
"rust compiler. Wheels\n"
"          with the native `linux` tag will be rejected by pypi, unless they "
"are separately validated\n"
"          by `auditwheel`.\n"
"\n"
"          The default is the lowest compatible `manylinux` tag, or plain "
"`linux` if nothing matched\n"
"\n"
"          This option is ignored on all non-linux platforms\n"
"\n"
"  -i, --interpreter [<INTERPRETER>...]\n"
"          The python versions to build wheels for, given as the executables "
"of interpreters such as\n"
"          `python3.9` or `/usr/bin/python3.8`\n"
"\n"
"  -f, --find-interpreter\n"
"          Find interpreters from the host machine\n"
"\n"
"  -b, --bindings <BINDINGS>\n"
"          Which kind of bindings to use\n"
"\n"
"          [possible values: pyo3, pyo3-ffi, rust-cpython, cffi, uniffi, "
"bin]\n"
"\n"
"  -o, --out <OUT>\n"
"          The directory to store the built wheels in. Defaults to a new "
"\"wheels\" directory in the\n"
"          project's target directory\n"
"\n"
"      --skip-auditwheel\n"
"          Don't check for manylinux compliance\n"
"\n"
"      --zig\n"
"          For manylinux targets, use zig to ensure compliance for the chosen "
"manylinux version\n"
"\n"
"          Default to manylinux2014/manylinux_2_17 if you do not specify an "
"`--compatibility`\n"
"\n"
"          Make sure you installed zig with `pip install maturin[zig]`\n"
"\n"
"      --universal2\n"
"          Control whether to build universal2 wheel for macOS or not. Only "
"applies to macOS targets,\n"
"          do nothing otherwise\n"
"\n"
"  -q, --quiet\n"
"          Do not print cargo log messages\n"
"\n"
"  -j, --jobs <N>\n"
"          Number of parallel jobs, defaults to # of CPUs\n"
"\n"
"      --profile <PROFILE-NAME>\n"
"          Build artifacts with the specified Cargo profile\n"
"\n"
"  -F, --features <FEATURES>\n"
"          Space or comma separated list of features to activate\n"
"\n"
"      --all-features\n"
"          Activate all available features\n"
"\n"
"      --no-default-features\n"
"          Do not activate the `default` feature\n"
"\n"
"      --target <TRIPLE>\n"
"          Build for the target triple\n"
"\n"
"          [env: CARGO_BUILD_TARGET=]\n"
"\n"
"      --target-dir <DIRECTORY>\n"
"          Directory for all generated artifacts\n"
"\n"
"  -m, --manifest-path <PATH>\n"
"          Path to Cargo.toml\n"
"\n"
"      --ignore-rust-version\n"
"          Ignore `rust-version` specification in packages\n"
"\n"
"  -v, --verbose...\n"
"          Use verbose output (-vv very verbose/build.rs output)\n"
"\n"
"      --color <WHEN>\n"
"          Coloring: auto, always, never\n"
"\n"
"      --frozen\n"
"          Require Cargo.lock and cache are up to date\n"
"\n"
"      --locked\n"
"          Require Cargo.lock is up to date\n"
"\n"
"      --offline\n"
"          Run without accessing the network\n"
"\n"
"      --config <KEY=VALUE>\n"
"          Override a configuration value (unstable)\n"
"\n"
"  -Z <FLAG>\n"
"          Unstable (nightly-only) flags to Cargo, see 'cargo -Z help' for "
"details\n"
"\n"
"      --timings=<FMTS>\n"
"          Timing output formats (unstable) (comma separated): html, json\n"
"\n"
"      --future-incompat-report\n"
"          Outputs a future incompatibility report at the end of the build "
"(unstable)\n"
"\n"
"  -h, --help\n"
"          Print help information (use `-h` for a summary)\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:196
msgid "Cross Compiling"
msgstr "交叉編譯"

#: src/distribution.md:198
msgid ""
"Maturin has decent cross compilation support for `pyo3` and `bin` bindings, "
"other kind of bindings may work but aren't tested regularly."
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:201
msgid "Cross-compile to Linux/macOS"
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:203
msgid "Use Docker"
msgstr "使用 Docker"

#: src/distribution.md:205
msgid ""
"For manylinux support the [manylinux-cross](https://github.com/rust-cross/"
"manylinux-cross) docker images can be used. And [maturin-action](https://"
"github.com/PyO3/maturin-action) makes it easy to do cross compilation on "
"GitHub Actions."
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:208
msgid "Use Zig"
msgstr "使用 Zig"

#: src/distribution.md:210
msgid ""
"Since v0.12.7 maturin added support for linking with [`zig cc`](https://"
"andrewkelley.me/post/zig-cc-powerful-drop-in-replacement-gcc-clang.html), "
"compile for  Linux works and is regularly tested on CI, other platforms may "
"also work but aren't tested regularly."
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:213
msgid ""
"You can install zig following the [official documentation](https://ziglang."
"org/download), or install it from PyPI via `pip install ziglang`. Then pass "
"`--zig` to maturin `build` or `publish` commands to use it, for example"
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:220
msgid "Cross-compile to Windows"
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:222
msgid ""
"Pyo3 0.16.5 added an experimental feature `generate-import-lib` enables the "
"user to cross compile extension modules for Windows targets without setting "
"the `PYO3_CROSS_LIB_DIR` environment variable or providing any Windows "
"Python library files."
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:226
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"[dependencies]\n"
"pyo3 = { version = \"0.18.0\", features = [\"extension-module\", \"generate-"
"import-lib\"] }\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:231
msgid ""
"It uses an external [`python3-dll-a`](https://docs.rs/python3-dll-a/latest/"
"python3_dll_a/) crate to generate import libraries for the Python DLL for "
"MinGW-w64 and MSVC compile targets. Note: MSVC targets require LLVM binutils "
"or MSVC build tools to be available on the host system. More specifically, "
"`python3-dll-a` requires `llvm-dlltool` or `lib.exe` executable to be "
"present in `PATH` when targeting `*-pc-windows-msvc`."
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:236
msgid ""
"maturin integrates [`cargo-xwin`](https://github.com/messense/cargo-xwin) to "
"enable MSVC targets cross compilation support, it will download and unpack "
"the Microsoft CRT headers and import libraries, and Windows SDK headers and "
"import libraries needed for compiling and linking automatically."
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:240
msgid ""
"**By using this to cross compiling to Windows MSVC targets you are consented "
"to accept the license at [https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkId=2086102]"
"(https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkId=2086102)**. (Building on Windows "
"natively does not apply.)"
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:243
msgid "GitHub Actions"
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:245
msgid ""
"If your project uses GitHub Actions, you can use the `maturin generate-ci` "
"command to generate a GitHub Actions workflow file."
msgstr ""

#: src/distribution.md:252
msgid "There are some options to customize the generated workflow file:"
msgstr ""
